{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491507"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:50:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:50:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"963"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/963"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.04,0.03,0.2,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"963"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106301"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/963"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"963"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88769"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1880"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"2571"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5808"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43050"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44262"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106301"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-year history of progressive breathlessness and lethargy. She can now only walk 50 metres before becoming breathless and has experienced several near-fainting episodes. She recently migrated from a country with limited healthcare access and has no documented medical history. She takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 115/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 90% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is peripheral cyanosis with digital clubbing and bruising on her upper limbs. Cardiac examination reveals a split second heart sound and a diastolic murmur heard best in the left second intercostal space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin: 195 g/L (115-165)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets: 450 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIron: 8 \u03bcmol/L (10-30)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransthoracic echocardiogram shows reduced biventricular function with right-to-left shunting demonstrated on agitated saline contrast study.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atrial septal defect","Transposition of the great arteries","Coarctation of the aorta","Tetralogy of Fallot","Eisenmenger syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of chronic cyanotic heart disease with secondary complications. The combination of progressive exercise intolerance, cyanosis, clubbing, secondary erythrocytosis, and right-to-left shunting on echocardiogram indicates advanced pulmonary vascular disease with shunt reversal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEisenmenger syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E develops when congenital heart defects with initial left-to-right shunting lead to progressive pulmonary hypertension and increased pulmonary vascular resistance. Eventually, pressures equalise and the shunt reverses to right-to-left, causing hypoxaemia and the clinical features seen here. The secondary erythrocytosis and thrombocytosis are compensatory responses to chronic hypoxaemia. Specific causes include: ventricular septal defect (VSD); atrial septal defect (ASD); atrioventricular septal defects, patent ductus arteriosus (PDA), as well as untreated tetralogy of Fallot (ToF).\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E in isolation typically presents earlier in life if symptomatic, and uncomplicated ASDs rarely cause significant symptoms in young adults. However, large unrepaired ASDs can progress to Eisenmenger physiology, which would then be classified as Eisenmenger syndrome rather than simple ASD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransposition of the great arteries\u003C/strong\u003E presents in the neonatal period with severe cyanosis and requires urgent intervention for survival. Patients with uncorrected transposition rarely survive to adulthood without complex surgical palliation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoarctation of the aorta\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with upper body hypertension, differential blood pressures between upper and lower limbs, and weak femoral pulses. The clinical features described are not consistent with coarctation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETetralogy of Fallot\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents in infancy with cyanotic episodes and requires early surgical correction. Uncorrected cases rarely survive to adulthood, and when they do, the diagnosis would be Eisenmenger syndrome if shunt reversal has occurred.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Eisenmenger syndrome develops when a left-to-right cardiac shunt leads to pulmonary hypertension and eventual shunt reversal.","Clinical features of Eisenmenger syndrome include cyanosis, clubbing, exercise intolerance, and secondary erythrocytosis.","Echocardiogram showing right-to-left shunting with elevated haemoglobin and platelets are characteristic findings in Eisenmenger syndrome."],"references":["Arvanitaki et al. Eisenmenger syndrome: diagnosis, prognosis and clinical management. Heart. 2020; 106: 1638-1645."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88769"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"963"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88769"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-17T19:19:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T19:20:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"963"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106301"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships"